"answer": 2,
"explain": "Choice C (correct). A performance obligation is a promise to transfer a good or service to a customer, and identifying it is step two of the five-step revenue recognition process. The transfer can be a contractual agreement to provide an individual good/service (or bundle) that is distinct for the customer, or a series of goods/services that are substantially the same and transferred in the same manner. Choice A. A promise by a customer to deliver consideration in the future is a promise to pay and is usually recognized as a payable once the seller has completed the performance obligation. A performance obligation is the obligation of the seller to provide a distinct good/service to the customer. Choice B. The decision to outsource tasks to meet a customer's specifications may be a condition of the overall contract, but the outsourcing itself is not the performance obligation, as the distinct good or service is not yet being provided to the customer. Choice D. Acquiring raw materials and supplies to prepare a product for sale is a necessary step in the manufacturing process, but it is not a performance obligation, because the completed product is not being transferred to the customer."
