"explain": "Choice D. Correct. Interest expense on a bond payable is the combination of interest paid and the amortization of either the discount or the premium. Interest payments on a fixed-rate bond are the same each period. For a discount bond, amortization causes the carrying value to move closer to face value each year, meaning the carrying value increases each year. Under the effective interest method, interest expense equals carrying value multiplied by the market interest rate at issuance. As the carrying value increases, interest expense increases by a larger amount each year. Choice A. Incorrect. Interest expense is the same each year only under the straight-line approach, not under the effective interest method for a discount bond. Choice B. Incorrect. Interest expense increases each year for a discount bond under the effective interest method, but not by the same amount. Choice C. Incorrect. Interest expense decreases each year for a premium bond, not a discount bond."
